### Reading Files in Rust

Rust provides multiple ways to read files, from simple convenience functions to buffered reading for large files.

---

### Reading Methods

| Method | Use Case |
|--------|----------|
| `fs::read_to_string(path)` | Read entire file as String (small files) |
| `fs::read(path)` | Read entire file as Vec<u8> (binary) |
| `File::open() + read_to_string()` | More control over reading |
| `BufReader` | Efficient line-by-line reading |

---

### Examples

```rust
use std::fs;
use std::io::{self, BufRead, BufReader, Read};

// Read entire file as string (most common for text)
let content = fs::read_to_string("file.txt")?;

// Read as bytes (binary files)
let bytes = fs::read("image.png")?;

// Read with BufReader (large files)
let file = File::open("large_file.txt")?;
let reader = BufReader::new(file);

for line in reader.lines() {
    let line = line?;
    println!("{}", line);
}

// Read with explicit buffer
let mut file = File::open("file.bin")?;
let mut buffer = Vec::new();
file.read_to_end(&mut buffer)?;

// Read exact number of bytes
let mut buf = [0u8; 1024];
file.read_exact(&mut buf)?;
```

> **Key Point:** For small text files, `fs::read_to_string` is the simplest approach. For large files, use `BufReader` with `lines()` for efficient line-by-line processing without loading the entire file into memory.

codeExample:
use std::fs;
use std::io::{BufRead, BufReader, Read};

fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {
    // Simple read
    let content = fs::read_to_string("Cargo.toml")?;
    println!("Cargo.toml contents:\n{}", content);

    // Line by line
    println!("\n--- Lines ---");
    for line in BufReader::new(fs::File::open("Cargo.toml")?).lines() {
        let line = line?;
        if !line.is_empty() {
            println!("> {}", line);
        }
    }

    Ok(())
}
